<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / International Company News: Heinz falls 12% in third quarter
on restructuring costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HJ Heinz, the Pittsburgh food group, yesterday posted a 12.2 per cent drop
in third-quarter net income, reflecting restructuring charges and higher
marketing costs.
Net income for the three months ended January 29 was Dollars 115.3m or 43
cents a share against Dollars 128.9m or 49 cents a year earlier. Sales were
essentially unchanged at Dollars 1.62bn against Dollars 1.61bn.
The company said the strength of the US dollar against foreign currencies
also contributed to the decline in the latest quarter.
Stripping out the impact of currency exchange rates, sales rose 5 per cent
in the latest quarter, reflecting volume increases in a number of brands,
including baby food, ketchup and cat food.
For the first nine months, Heinz's net income advanced 19.6 per cent to
Dollars 492.6m or Dollars 1.84 a share, including a one-off pre-tax gain of
Dollars 221m from the sale of Hubinger in June. A year earlier, the company
earned Dollars 411.9m or Dollars 1.55 a share. Sales eased to Dollars 4.71bn
from Dollars 4.81bn a year ago.
On Wall Street, shares in Heinz firmed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 37 in
moderate volume.
During the latest third quarter, the company's gross profits fell 3.4 per
cent to Dollars 604.9m from Dollars 626.1m. Selling, general and
administrative expenses were Dollars 390m against Dollars 388.1m in the 1990
quarter.
Mr Tony O'Reilly, chairman, reiterated his forecast of growth of about 12
per cent in earnings per share and net income for the full year.
</TEXT>
