FT  10 MAR 92 / Shares in MTM fall after new warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MTM, the specialist chemicals supplier, shed half its market capitalisation
at one stage yesterday after it made its second profits warning in a week.
Its shares, which began the day at 189p, fell to below 90p before closing at
119p.
Shareholders and analysts questioned why the Stock Exchange had not
suspended the shares before the announcement.
One analyst said the market in MTM shares had deteriorated into a 'casino'
after the announcement.
He had written a buy recommendation after Mr Richard Lines, chairman and
chief executive, told analysts last week at the offices of Robert Fleming,
MTM's merchant bank, that there were no problems with 1991 trading profits.
MTM's warning last Monday said profits would be substantially below City
expectations - then at Pounds 23m - because its auditors, Binder Hamlyn,
were taking a tougher view on the valuation of fixed assets. Before that
announcement, MTM's shares were at 286p.
With the company adding little to its statement that it was now facing a
'significant' shortfall in trading profits over expectations, some
shareholders were questioning whether Mr Lines could stay on as chairman and
chief executive.
Neither Mr Lines nor Mr Tom Baxter, MTM's finance director, who met analysts
last week after the company's first announcement, was available for comment.
One institutional investor bought shares last week after the first sharp
price fall when he was assured that 1991 trading was unaffected by the
difference of opinion with the auditors.
He said he could see no reason why Mr Lines should mislead the market about
profits and he had no idea why these profits suddenly appeared to have hit a
wall.
Mr Lines, who founded the company in 1979 after 11 years with ICI, owns 7
per cent of MTM.
Last week's announcement that MTM had fallen foul of the auditors,
particularly over capitalisation of development costs and some fixed assets,
took few in the City entirely by surprise.
But the group's admission that trading had fallen short of expectations
shocked analysts.
'Last week it was an accounting problem; this week it is a trading problem,'
one analyst said. Lex, Page 22
