FT  10 MAR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is Norman's big day and the question is: will he or won't he? Wear yet
another new sweater with a funny design, that is. Regular viewers of Film 92
are as likely to turn on for Barry Norman's woollies as to see which movies
he is reviewing. Today's films include the British-made 'Hear My Song' about
Irish tenor Josef Locke which is receiving a lot of attention in the US as
well as the UK (10.30 BBC1).
FT readers with nothing better to do may want to have a look, earlier in the
day, at what Norman Lamont is up to. The Chancellor should stand up in the
House at 3.30 but Budget 92 with David Dimbleby, safest hands in the
business, begins at 2.30 on BBC2. For those with no television but a
wireless, Radio 4 starts PM Budget Special, Valerie Singleton presenting, at
3.00. ITN wades in at 3.15 on ITV with a team headed by Alistair Stewart,
John Suchet and Julia Somerville.
Channel 4 presents 'a modern fairy tale play combining fact and fiction to
mark Adult Learners' Week': Homer And His Pigeons (8.00). That is followed
by the C4 arts programme Without Walls which today considers what 12 years
of Conservative government have done to culture (9.00).
