<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Armenian forces attack ex-Soviet military base
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, BRUSSELS, BAKU, AZERBAIJAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DOZENS of heavily armed Armenian militants surrounded a former Soviet
anti-aircraft missile base inside Armenia yesterday, killing two soldiers of
the Commonwealth of Independent States and taking the commander hostage,
Reuter reports from Moscow.
About 60 Armenians, who launched the attack on Sunday night at Artik, near
the Turkish border, were demanding the handover of heavy weapons for their
war against Azerbaijan, according to the CIS military command.
The two former Soviet republics are fighting for control of
Nagorno-Karabakh, the Armenian-dominated enclave within Azerbaijan. Both
sides have reported death tolls in the hundreds in the past two weeks. More
than 1,500 have died in four years of warfare.
Howitzers and tank guns boomed across the disputed enclave yesterday,
drowning out talk of peace between the two sides.
Elsewhere in the former Soviet Union, violence continued in the month-long
civil war in Georgia. An explosion in the town of Zugdidi, in the west of
the republic , killed three policemen and injured several others.
In the republic of Moldova yesterday, peace talks were due to start after a
week of clashes between ethnic Russians and majority Romanian speakers in
which at least 10 people have been killed.
John Lloyd, in Baku, Azerbaijan, adds: Nationalist leaders in Azerbaijan
yesterday stepped up the pressure on the interim government of the republic
to dissolve parliament and to form a coalition government with a strong
contingent of nationalists and former opposition figures. The aim of such a
coalition would be to pursue a more active prosecution of the conflict in
Nagorno Karabakh - to hit back at the Armenian forces after a string of
reverses.
Mr Niazi Ibragimov, deputy chairman of the Azerbaijani Popular Front - the
focus for opposition nationalist forces - called for the dissolution of
parliament and the passing of more power to the 50-strong National Council.
The council is equally balanced between oppositionists and former communists
whose orientation is now uncertain in the wake of the resignation last week
of President Ayaz Mutalibov, a former leader of the Azerbaijani communist
party.
Kazakhstan told Nato yesterday it would not attend the meeting of the
Co-operation Council that will draw former Soviet republics into an
east-west forum on security, Reuter reports from Brussels. The republic said
it was unable to attend 'for practical reasons'. Kazakhstan has already
failed to turn up to other meetings at Nato to discuss arms control.
</TEXT>
