<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 92 / Berlin to launch pay strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FIRST wave of official warning strikes among public sector employees is
expected to hit Germany today following a call for action yesterday from the
leadership of the DAG white-collar workers' union, writes Christopher
Parkes.
Angered by last week's 3.5 per cent pay offer in the face of its 10.5 per
cent claim, the union said government, state and local authorities had
inflamed the situation and had 'obviously adopted a strategy of conflict'.
Protest stoppages, due to start in Berlin this morning, are expected to
spread across the country between now and the next round of negotiations,
due on March 19.
Rail passengers in the Cologne area were given their first taste of trouble
to come yesterday when, according to the local rail authorities, 'a handful'
of level crossing and signal box workers delayed nine trains for up to 20
minutes.
Meanwhile, the government, which is determined to rein in pay increases in
all sectors, sent further signals that it is not willing to sacrifice
economic and monetary stability to unreasonable pay claims.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl told regional party leaders of his Christian
Democratic Union (CDU) that German stability was important both at home and
abroad.
'If we go down on our knees then the (economic) improvements in the new
federal states will be further slowed,' he said in Bonn.
Mr Jurgen Mollemann, economics minister, said pay awards must be related to
the current economic conditions. The minister, who has been widely attacked
for his insistence that increases must be held below 5 per cent, said that
if demands were not restrained the west German economy faced more than
'short-term disruption'.
OTV, the largest of the two main public service unions which together
represent some 2.3m workers, said at the weekend that unless the employers
improved their offer at the next round of talks the negotiations would be
formally ended and a strike ballot called.
Its leaders are also expected to call warning strikes within the next few
days, adding weight to the DAG initiative.
</TEXT>
