<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / 'Big bang' BR sale dropped: Denationalisation of the
railways could stretch into the next decade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS have formally agreed to abandon plans to privatise British Rail in
one 'big bang' within the lifetime of the next parliament.
Instead, the Conservative party election manifesto will pave the way for a
creeping denationalisation of the railways which could stretch beyond the
end of the decade.
The turnabout appears to have resulted from a recognition of the
overwhelming practical difficulties facing any of the suggested options for
breaking up BR and selling it outright.
It is likely to be seen as a victory for Sir Bob Reid, whose short career as
BR's chairman had seemed destined to culminate in the break-up and abolition
of the corporation within the next five years.
It will also feed the belief among some observers that privatisation plans
have been undermined by a reluctance among Department of Transport officials
to see their power base eroded.
Under the new plan, privatisation - or denationalisation, as transport
ministers are now calling it - will be a gradual process. The first step
will be to remove BR's statutory monopoly and open the tracks to anyone who
wants to operate trains. This will mean setting up a regulatory authority to
ensure all operators have equal access to tracks and stations.
The next step will be to sell Railfreight, BR's freight division, to the
private sector. This can be done quickly because the division has good
profits potential and its trains do not carry voters.
Finally, the government will seek a slow and cautious transfer of BR's
passenger services - but not its tracks - to the private sector.
Services, or groups of services, which deliver returns high enough to
satisfy the private sector could be sold outright. Loss-making but socially
necessary services could be franchised out to operators requiring the lowest
subsidies.
Eventually, when all Britain's train services are being operated by the
private sector, BR could be left as a residuary body, owning just the
tracks. But the scale of investment needed to bring some services to
profitability means this stage is unlikely to be reached until well into the
next decade.
A high priority for ministers has been the need to allay voters' fears that
a 'big bang' privatisation could mean higher fares and service cuts.
The plans appear to differ markedly from those Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the
transport secretary, advocated last year, but Mr Rifkind has thrown his
weight behind them, letting it be known that he is 'delighted'.
Backtracking on sale, page 14
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
