<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Scepticism reported on redress
payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMERS of government agencies appear to be unconvinced of the merits of
compensation payments when service falls below standard, John Willman
writes.
Such redress systems are at the centre of the government's Citizen's
Charter, but people would prefer agencies to 'get it right first time', says
a report published by Price Waterhouse, the accountancy firm.
Response speed and reliability were rated as the most important priorities
in the surveys by which many agencies measure customer satisfaction. Methods
of redress were rated least important behind staff courtesy and the
condition of public areas. The report was based on interviews with chief
executives of 42 of the 57 agencies established to improve government
services.
Unsuitable staff and shortage of financial resources were cited as the most
common obstacles to providing better service.
Executive agencies: Facts and Trends. Price Waterhouse, 1 Moor Lane, London
EC2Y 9PB. Free.
</TEXT>
