<DATE>920309
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Unions set to agree changes at Rover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS AT the Rover vehicle group are likely to recommend proposals for
Japanese-style changes in working practices to their 30,000 members at the
company after talks with management.
The company said last week that, after more than five months of negotiations
between management and unions, the talks had been successfully concluded.
Representatives of the AEU engineering workers' and TGWU general workers'
unions on the joint negotiating committee at Rover are likely to pave the
way today for the main proposals. The union will then call a meeting of
delegates from all sites to consider the proposals, which will later be
presented to the workforce for a ballot.
Mr John Allen, the AEU's chief Rover negotiator, said yesterday that the
deal would 'strengthen the future viability of Rover'.
The agreement is designed to help the company meet increasing competition
from Japanese car plants in the UK and elsewhere in Europe. Much of the
proposed plan is based on Japanese working methods.
The package, which would increase job security for workers by removing the
threat of compulsory redundancies, would eliminate nearly all shopfloor
demarcation lines and clear the way for flexible team working.
The measures would create a single-status company by ending all remaining
distinctions been staff and hourly-paid workers, including ending
clocking-on arrangements for manual workers.
</TEXT>
