<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / UK News (Employment): Call to reform race discrimination
laws
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SWEEPING REFORMS are needed to make race discrimination laws effective,
according to government research. Existing laws are so heavily weighted
against victims that the vast majority of offences go unpunished, according
to a study published today.
The Commission for Racial Equality has argued for some years that reform is
needed, but the government has said it considers existing laws to be
adequate. Today's report was compiled by the University of Southampton for
the Department of Employment.
It says employers should be required by law to take steps to ensure ethnic
minorities are recruited and promoted. 'Class actions', along the lines of
the US system, should be introduced which would allow cases to be brought on
behalf of groups in society. The study argues that the commission should
also be given greater powers of investigation.
While Britain's race laws are among the most extensive in the European
Community, the study says victims of discrimination are 'discouraged by
every step' of the legal process. Emotional stress and fear of victimisation
'act as further disincentives'.
The study concludes that in spite of considerable legal and practical
measures the evidence shows 'the vast majority of instances of
discrimination are untested and go unpunished under the current
arrangements'.
Measure for Measure. Research Management Branch, Employment Department, Room
W441, Moorfoot, Sheffield S1 4PQ. Free.
</TEXT>
