<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / Transport system in chaos, say architects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S architects say that the country faces a severe housing crisis and
that its transport system is in chaos.
The Royal Institute of British Architects today urges changes in government
policies on housing, transport and the environment. 'The housing needs of
many members of society are not being met,' it says.
The paper says public expenditure on housing has fallen 60 per cent in real
terms over the past 10 years. Local authority house-building has fallen from
86,000 units in 1980 to 13,000 units last year. Housing associations built
17,000 houses last year compared with 21,000 in 1980.
It calls for a national housing policy to establish the extent of housing
shortages, the areas where new housing is required, and the type of housing
needed.
Local authorities should be allowed to spend a far greater proportion of
capital receipts from the sale of housing and land on building new homes,
the institute says.
Leading financial institutions should be encouraged to play a part in the
private-rented sector.
'Adequate standards of housing for all sectors of the community are an
essential human right,' the institute's paper continues. 'It should not be
left to the market to determine the nation's housing mix on the basis of the
best possible return on site value.'
The paper says that a balance must be struck within the next generation
between private and public transport, and road and rail. 'More road building
is not the solution to the problem of traffic in town and cities,' it says.
Without efficient public transport towns and cities will be condemned to
terminal decline.'
Some further selective investment will be needed in motorways and trunk
roads but there is no case for introducing toll roads, it argues.
Railways are the most effective means of mass transportation and a target
should be set for the transfer of freight from road to rail, the paper says.
But more public investment and subsidy will be needed to maintain and
improve rail services. 'Privatisation will not ensure an improved railway
network.'
An Agenda for the Nineties, RIBA, 66 Portland Place, London W1N 4AD.
British Pavilion, Page 13
</TEXT>
