<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / Devolution may cloud Lib Dems' message
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGE in Britain's political system and economic revival were set at the
centre of Liberal Democrat aspirations for the general election yesterday by
Mr Paddy Ashdown, party leader. But he risked clouding his party's message
with a complex stance on the issue of 'home rule' for Scotland.
'Never before has the ground for political change been so well prepared,' he
said at his party's spring conference in Glasgow.
On the economy, he warned that 'the Tories offer paralysis and Labour offer
timidity'. He called for more public investment and an independent central
bank, and hinted that he would reverse any tax cuts in tomorrow's Budget.
He welcomed the possibility that steps towards proportional representation
might appear in the Labour manifesto. But he urged the party to go farther,
'bite the bullet' and come out unequivocally in favour of reform.
In spite of the obvious passion of Liberal Democrats at Glasgow for Scottish
'home rule', the party's MPs have agreed it must be subordinate to Mr
Ashdown's top priority - electoral reform at Westminster. Some MPs have had
to be persuaded to toe the line, notably Sir David Steel, the former Liberal
party leader who made only a brief appearance at the conference. With
devolution bounding up the Scottish political agenda, the strength of the
deal to subordinate Scottish aspirations has been tested to the limit. Mr
Malcolm Bruce, Scottish spokesman, admitted the party was only 'half way'
towards persuading voters to accept why Scotland would not have a guarantee
of its rights under a devolved system until Britain had a fair and
representative democracy.
Mr Ashdown knows the Liberal Democrats' appeal has to be broadly based if he
is to make an impact in the constituencies in southern England from which
the Liberal Democrats were forged - came second to the Tories in 1987.
Scottish 'home rule' is far down the list of voters' priorities in Liberal
Democrat target seats such as Bath, Falmouth and Camborne, Richmond and
Barnes, or Cheltenham. Mr Ashdown's tactics for capturing such seats are
based on simple messages about changing the Westminster political system and
on disenchantment with 'negative' Labour and Tory campaigning.
The Liberal Democrats' slogan My Vote, splashed across a giant orange sun
above the conference platform, is aimed at encouraging voters to make every
ballot paper count. Party political broadcasts will list all the 259
constituencies where the Liberal Democrat is the main challenger to the MP.
'Ours will be the vote which breaks the logjam holding back change in our
country . . . My vote is for an election which is positive,' read the
introduction to Mr Ashdown's speech.
That message will be emphasised at grassroots level with Liberal Democrat
policy papers crammed with neat ideas or 'common sense' solutions to
contemporary issues - such as the housing shortage or animal rights - that
can be niche-marketed according to local concerns.
Party headquarters in Westminster is lean and professional - a remarkable
turnround compared with the near-bankrupt state of the organisation a few
years ago.
But the lesson of past elections is that Liberal Democrat victories are born
largely of local effort.
Party strategists believe a coalition government is a long way down the
scale of probabilities. They fully expect Labour or the Tories to attempt to
run a minority government before calling Mr Ashdown.
Liberal Democrat MPs in Scotland feel joy at the way in which the 'home
rule' dream that drove many of them into politics could soon start to become
reality. Their delight could threaten the party's cohesion if Mr Ashdown
sought to vote down a minority government offering devolution, but not full
constitutional reform.
A substantial minority of Scottish companies expect constitutional change in
Scotland after the general election, even though a majority expect the
election will be won by the Conservative party, which opposes constitutional
change, James Buxton writes.
Two thirds of Scottish companies expect the Tories to win the election,
according to a survey by BBC Scotland and Pannell Kerr Forster, the
accountancy firm.
</TEXT>
