<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / Recovery put at heart of Tory election strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INTENSE campaign to persuade voters that a fourth Conservative term is a
prere-quisite for the economy's emergence from recession has been put at the
centre of Mr John Major's general election strategy.
As the prime minister trailed his manifesto at a weekend conference of party
activists he stressed that the promised economic recovery depended on a
Conservative victory. Among the pledges in the manifesto will be a fresh
drive to regenerate the inner cities.
His comments coincided with a signal from Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, that the Tories will make maximum capital during the
campaign out of the past and present links of Labour MPs with leftwing
causes.
Mr Heseltine, a member of the government's election 'A-Team', said the
Conservatives would emphasise repeatedly that any parliamentary majority
secured by Mr Neil Kinnock would leave the Labour leader 'totally dependent
on his party's extremist wing'.
Since the start of the year Mr Major has been blaming the length of the
recession on the world economic downturn. Senior colleagues said that
approach had been judged a success. The aim now was to combine the voters'
awareness of the worsening international outlook with a perception that the
upturn in Britain was being delayed also by political uncertainty.
Mr Major told the party's weekend local government conference that a
Conservative victory was 'crucial' because: 'Britain is ready to come out of
recession - and only a Conservative government can safely bring it out.'
The prime minister added: 'What the country needs now, above all, is
confidence . . . and if confidence in business is to grow, there's nothing
that will make it grow faster than a Conservative victory at the general
election.'
That theme will be echoed throughout the four-week campaign proper which Mr
Major is expected to launch when he asks the Queen to dissolve parliament
after tomorrow's Budget. It will be used to answer Opposition charges that
the government miscalculated the depth and duration of the recession and to
move on to the offensive against Labour.
A succession of senior ministers warned at the weekend that Labour's
'high-tax, high-spending, high-inflation' policies would wreck any prospect
of an economic upturn.
Mr Major confirmed that opportunity, choice, ownership and individual
responsibility would be the principal themes underlying the manifesto which
the Conservatives plan to publish early next week.
He was joined by colleagues in emphasising that a commitment to improved
public services would also be writ large in the Conservative prospectus.
Mr Heseltine promised a large-scale initiative to bring together public and
private finance to regenerate inner cities. His comments suggest that, after
a difficult battle with cabinet colleagues, he has won the prime minister's
approval to extend greatly the present City Challenge programme.
</TEXT>
