<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / Labour raises stakes on constitutional reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR will today seek to broaden its constitutional debate and will include
in it proportional representation, which will be crucial in the event of a
hung parliament.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow trade and industry secretary, will spell out the
need for a new constitutional settlement between the individual, the
community and the government.
As proportional representation is again highlighted as a way in which Labour
could attract support away from the Liberal Democrats, Mr Brown will make
the case for a broader constitutional agenda. This would include freedom of
information, devolution, moves towards a written constitution and the
concept of economic rights.
In the first of a series of lectures organised by Charter 88, the
constitutional reform movement, Mr Brown is expected to argue that the
post-war settlement did not take account of government itself as a vested
interest from which the citizen might need protection. While Mrs Thatcher in
1979 represented some attempt to redress the balance, she did so by denying
the existence of community altogether.
Mr Brown will say that constitutional change 'is not incidental but integral
to our future as a country. It is not a sideshow at the election but centre
stage'.
Labour yesterday played down the prospect of a potentially divisive
manifesto commitment to proportional representation for parliamentary
elections. Party officials said the manifesto would not offer a royal
commission or Speaker's conference, but would promise the enhancement of the
work of the committee on electoral reform chaired by Professor Raymond
Plant.
Mr Robin Cook, the shadow health secretary and a supporter of electoral
reform, said yesterday: 'The Plant committee's work will continue in
government and of course it will be a much more powerful and influential
body then because it will not be a sub-committee of an opposition, it will
be a committee, a strengthened committee, reporting to a government with
power to act.'
Labour, which is slightly ahead of the Tories according to the opinion
polls, is confident that the Budget, which will dominate this week, will
have little effect on voting.
The party believes that its 'borrowing to bribe' campaign during the past
few weeks has neutralised the effect of any tax cuts, while a package of
measures intended to bring about recovery will, it argues, enable it to
claim that it has won the argument.
Three of Labour's senior performers will lead the attack in the first few
days after the election is expected to have been called.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the party leader, will speak at the Scottish Labour
conference on Friday. Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, and Mr Roy
Hattersley, the party's deputy leader, will speak at the party's London
conference next weekend.
Today Mr Cook will highlight the clear choice between the 'bribe' of tax
cuts and more spending on health care.
In an interview on TV-am yesterday he sought to keep up the pressure on the
government over the health service, with renewed claims that it was harder
for doctors to use clinical judgment because they were being pressed to use
commercial judgment.
</TEXT>
