<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / National housing bank proposals published
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR HAS published its plans for a national housing bank to increase the
supply of homes for rent without adding directly to government spending.
The bank would borrow money on the capital markets and lend it to local
authorities and housing associations to build and renovate rented housing.
Private landlords could also be given access to funds for rented
accommodation, provided they observed tenants' rights and kept the housing
in good repair. Finance could be offered to housebuilders to support social
housing in mixed developments to foster balanced communities.
The bank would be established as a public limited company so that it could
be set up relatively quickly. Its borrowing would thus not be included in
the Public Sector Borrowing Requirement (PSBR), and would be free of
Treasury restrictions. The bank would offer a way of recycling local
authority capital receipts back into housing without adding to the PSBR.
At present, spending these receipts counts towards the PSBR, and councils
can plough back only a proportion of the money into housing. Money invested
in the national housing bank would not count as part of the PSBR, even if it
were spent on housing.
The plans are likely to be welcomed by those who believe that the level of
building for rent needs to be increased substantially.
The scheme has been welcomed by builders' representatives. Mr John Smith,
chairman of the Building Employers' Federation, said: 'Something of this
sort already exists in one or two European countries. Anything which can
increase the flow of housing finance without adding to inflation must be
welcome'.
</TEXT>
