<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Pierre Beregovoy, French finance minister, said yesterday that Mr
Jean-Marie Le Pen, the ultra-right leader, posed a threat to democracy and
likened his rise to that of Adolf Hitler and Benito Mussolini, Reuter
reports from Paris.
'We must realise that Le Pen's ideas threaten to be fatal for democracy. All
democrats . . . must clearly say 'Never, never will we ally ourselves with
Le Pen',' Mr Beregovoy told French television.
'I am among those who as an adolescent lived through the events of 1939 to
1945.
'I knew how Hitler and Mussolini took power, by flirting with the most
perverse elements of human consciousness,' he said.
The Socialists, expected to take a battering in regional elections on March
22, have made the fight against Mr Le Pen's National Front one of the
central themes of their campaign.
On Friday, left-wing demonstrators hurled petrol bombs at National Front's
Rouen headquarters.
