<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / Architects urge policy change for housing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S architects say that the country faces a dramatic housing crisis
and that its transport system is in chaos.
The Royal Institute of British Architects urges changes in government
policies on housing, transport and the environment in its paper An Agenda
for the Nineties, published today.
'The housing needs of many members of society are not being met,' it says.
The paper says public expenditure on housing has fallen 60 per cent in real
terms over the past 10 years. Local authority house-building has fallen from
86,000 units in 1980 to 13,000 units last year. Housing associations built
17,000 houses last year compared with 21,000 in 1980.
It calls for a national housing policy to establish the extent of housing
shortages, the areas where new housing is required, and the type of housing
needed.
Local authorities should be allowed to spend a far greater proportion of
capital receipts from the sale of housing and land on building new homes, it
says. Leading financial institutions should be encouraged to play a part in
the private-rented sector.
'Adequate standards of housing for all sectors of the community are an
essential human right. It should not be left to the market to determine the
nation's housing mix on the basis of the best possible return on site
value.'
The paper says that a balance must be struck within the next generation
between private and public transport, and road and rail. 'More road building
is not the solution to the problem of traffic in town and cities. Without
efficient public transport towns and cities will be condemned to terminal
decline,' it says.
Some further selective investment will be needed in motorways and trunk
roads but there is no case for introducing toll roads, it argues.
Railways are the most effective means of mass transportation and a target
should be set for the transfer of freight from road to rail, the paper says.
But more public investment and subsidy will be needed to maintain and
improve rail services. 'Privatisation will not ensure an improved railway
network.'
The paper, which says that architectural competitions should be held for all
major buildings, attacks government proposals to introduce compulsory
competitive tendering for local authority architects' departments, deriding
the 'assumption that the cheapest architect will provide taxpayers with the
best value'.
An Agenda for the Nineties, RIBA, 66 Portland Place, London W1N 4AD.
Tony Andrews Road to ruin: 'Without efficient public transport, towns and
cities will be condemned to terminal decline'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
