<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 92 / Stance on Scotland may cloud Lib Dem message
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGE in Britain's political system and economic revival were set at the
centre of Liberal Democrat aspirations for the general election yesterday by
Mr Paddy Ashdown, party leader. But he risked clouding his party's message
with a complex stance on the issue of 'home rule' for Scotland.
Rallying his party at its spring conference in Glasgow, Mr Ashdown
confronted accusations that a Liberal Democrat vote is a wasted vote. 'Never
before has the ground for political change been so well prepared,' he said.
On the economy, he warned that 'the Tories offer paralysis and Labour offer
timidity.' He called for public investment, an independent central bank -
and hinted that he would reverse any tax cuts in tomorrow's Budget.
He welcomed moves by Labour in the direction of including moves towards
proportional representation in its manifesto. But the party should go
farther, 'bite the bullet' and come out unequivocally in favour of reform.
In spite of the obvious passion of Liberal Democrats at Glasgow for Scottish
'home rule', the party's MPs have agreed it must be subordinate to Mr
Ashdown's top priority - electoral reform at Westminster. Some MPs have had
to be persuaded to toe the line, notably Sir David Steel, the former Liberal
party leader who made only a very brief appearance at the conference. With
devolution bounding up the Scottish political agenda, the strength of the
deal to subordinate Scottish aspirations has been tested to the limit. Mr
Malcolm Bruce, Scottish spokesman, admitted the party was only 'half way'
towards persuading voters why Scotland would not have a guarantee of its
rights under a devolved system until Britain had a fair and representative
democracy.
Liberal Democrat MPs in Scotland feel glee at the way in which the 'home
rule' dream that drove many of them into politics in the 1960s and 1970s
could start to become a reality in five weeks. Their delight is an emotion
that could threaten the party's cohesion if Mr Ashdown sought to vote down a
minority government offering devolution but not full-blown constitutional
reform.
Yet Mr Ashdown knows the Liberal Democrats' appeal has to be broader based
if he is to make an impact in the constituencies in the south-west and
south-east of England where the Alliance parties - from which the Liberal
Democrats were forged - came second to the Tories in 1987.
The Scottish MPs do not need special concessions. In all but one of the
constituencies, the main challenger is the Conservative party, not Labour or
the Scottish nationalists.
Scottish 'home rule' is far down the list of voters' priorities in Liberal
Democrat target seats such as Bath, Falmouth and Camborne, Richmond and
Barnes, or Cheltenham. Mr Ashdown's tactics for capturing such seats are
broader and softer focused, based on simple messages about changing the
Westminster political system, of building on voter apathy or disenchantment
with negative Labour and Tory campaigning.
The party's My Vote slogan, splashed across a giant orange sun over the
conference platform, is aimed at encouraging voters to make every ballot
paper count. Party political broadcasts will list all the 259 constituencies
where the Liberal Democrat is the main challenger to the MP.
'Ours will be the vote which breaks the logjam holding back change in our
country . . . My vote is for an election which is positive,' read the
introduction to Mr Ashdown's speech.
That message will be emphasised at grassroots level with Liberal Democrat
policy papers crammed with neat ideas or 'common sense' solutions to
contemporary issues - such as the housing shortage or animal rights - that
can be niche-marketed according to local concerns.
Party headquarters in Westminster is lean and professional - a remarkable
turnround compared with the near-bankrupt state of the organisation a few
years ago. But the lesson of past elections is that Liberal Democrat
victories are borne largely of local effort.
Alas for Mr Ashdown, the devolution debate was in danger over the weekend of
disguising the infectious enthusiasm of confident Liberal Democrat
candidates. He risks exacerbating the confusion himself. He appeases home
rulers by talking of the Scottish devolution debate as 'the soft underbelly'
of UK constitutional reform but - apparently in contradiction - says a
Scottish parliament could not become entrenched if a single party at
Westminster could impose the policies that Scotland had rejected.
The hypothetical arguments over what his stance would mean in a hung
parliament - like the fascination over how many cabinet seats Mr Ashdown
might or might not demand - irritate party strategists who believe a
coalition government is a long way down the scale of probabilities.
In practice they fully expect Labour or the Tories to attempt to run a
minority government before calling Mr Ashdown. If the government survived
the Queen's speech debate, Liberal Democrats would vote for any devolution
legislation brought before parliament.
Trevor Humphries Reaching for the top: Paddy Ashdown flanked at the Glasgow
conference yesterday by Lord Jenkins (left), Charles Kennedy, Liberal
Democrat president, with Robert MacLennan, former SDP leader, in the
background
</TEXT>
