FT  09 MAR 92 / Japan's ruling party defeated in by-election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) was defeated at an important
by-election yesterday, heightening pressure within the party for Mr Kiichi
Miyazawa to step down as prime minister to appease voters disillusioned with
the scandal-tainted government.
The upper house poll in Miyagi, in northern Japan, was narrowly won by a
trade union candidate backed by the Social Democratic Party of Japan, which
had taken the seat in 1989 when the LDP was troubled by an earlier set of
corruption scandals.
In conceding defeat, Mr Miyazawa said that the party had waged an 'excellent
fight' in attempting to regain the seat, but the result and a low voter
turnout highlighted public disaffection with the LDP.
Opposition politicians said the outcome was a significant victory for them,
and showed that the public wanted reforms of the scandal-prone political
system. Mr Tamisuke Watanuki, the LDP secretary-general, said that 'we
deeply regret' failing to win and will 'do our best to revive public trust'.
Mr Miyazawa had campaigned on behalf of his party, although the local
campaign manager had suggested that it would in the LDP's best interests if
the prime minister stayed away.
The branch had wanted to focus its campaign on local issues, drawing
attention away from the scandals at the party's centre.
The Miyagi area is also an important rice-growing district, and it was
expected that some farmers, traditional LDP supporters, would have deserted
the party or not voted as a protest against the expected liberalisation of
Japan's rice market.
</TEXT>
