<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Kunick raises Pounds 5.6m from Dungeons
sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KUNICK, the amusement machine and nursing home group, yesterday released its
second profits warning in less than six months and said that it was selling
the London and York Dungeons for Pounds 5.6m.
The company blamed the recessions in the UK and France, which had been
longer than expected.
It said first half profits to end-March would be 'substantially below' the
Pounds 7.3m last time. The shares, which traded at 36p before the first
profits warning in October, fell a further 2p to 9p.
UK amusement machine business continued to be hit by the economic downturn
and uncertainty following the Monopolies and Mergers Commission report on
beer supply, the company said.
Kunick has previously estimated that between 10,000 to 15,000 pubs have
ceased trading during the recession.
Mr Russell Smith, chairman, said care services were performing
satisfactorily, except for sale and rental of close care and sheltered
housing units which continued to be affected by the state of the housing
market.
He added that it was impossible to predict group trading levels in the
second half of this year.
Kunick plans a further review of operations and will reduce borrowings
through the sale of The London Dungeon and The York Dungeon tourist sites
for Pounds 5.6m to Winchmore.
Winchmore is itself being restructured following the resignation of the
existing management and the appointment of Mr David Hudd, a non-executive
director of Kunick, as chairman.
Winchmore will pay for the acquisition through a placing of 17.9m new shares
at 40p to raise Pounds 6.8m. The company also plans to change its name to
Vardon.
The London Dungeon attracted 434,000 visitors in the year to end-September,
down from about 500,000 the previous year, with 123,000 visitors at York.
The two sites made trading profits of Pounds 1.26m from turnover of Pounds
2.22m during the period.
</TEXT>
