<TEXT>
Cray Electronics, the software systems, telecommunications and
instrumentation group, is paying Pounds 16.8m for Autofile, a software
specialist best known for its ATOP holiday reservation system, writes Angus
Foster.
Cray also expects to pay its first dividend since 1989 when it announces
results for the year to end-April. The dividend was suspended after new
management under Sir Peter Michael took over the company, which had been
rocked by overspending and overstated profits.
Autofile made pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.3m from sales of Pounds 16.1m last
year. More than 80 per cent of sales were due to ATOP, which is used by tour
operators like Owners Abroad and Virgin Holidays.
Cray will pay for the purchase through the issue of 27.8m new shares.
A total of 4.2m shares will remain with Autofile's existing shareholders,
mainly senior management. A further 23.6m shares are being placed by SG
Warburg and offered to Cray shareholders on the basis of one new share for
every 4.5184 existing shares at 61p.
