<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 92 / Aerospace industry calls for more government aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AEROSPACE industry, struggling under defence cuts and the downturn in
civil business, is launching a campaign to coincide with the start of the
general election to seek greater government support.
On Monday the Society of British Aerospace Companies will send a series of
briefing papers to potential parliamentary candidates from all parties
warning them of the plight of the aerospace industry and the repercussions
on jobs and technology in industry as a whole.
The society warns that aerospace industry employment will fall as much as 25
per cent - or about 44,000 jobs  - between 1989 and this year because of
defence cuts and the civil aerospace recession. It estimates employment in
its 240 member companies will fall from 194,000 jobs in 1989 to about
150,000 by the end of this year. 'Further job losses will take place in
small companies providing services and goods to the aerospace industry,' it
says.
A society official said yesterday that aerospace workers were voters in 340
constituencies. Of these, two thirds were regarded as among the top marginal
constituencies in the forthcoming election.
Sir Ralph Robins, the chief executive of Rolls-Royce, the UK aero-engine
group, yesterday stressed that the UK aerospace industry required the same
'level playing field' as rival aerospace industries, which were facing the
same pressures of defence cuts and a downturn in civil orders.
He told the Aviation Club of Britain: 'Some of our foreign friends receive
considerable help from their governments. Either we have to stop these
governments doing this or we must join them and help our industry in the
same way.'
The society is pressing for a closer dialogue between companies and
government to ensure that the UK maintains the optimum defence industrial
base and leading-edge technological competence in spite of restructuring.
The decision to reduce defence equipment expenditure was taken by one
government department, the Ministry of Defence, but the industrial
restructuring has consequences for and requires action from several other
government departments including trade, transport and employment, the
society argues.
It also urges: Increased government investment in new space and civil
aerospace projects.
Government launch funds for civil aerospace projects should be expanded to
include components and avionics.
European Community recognition that the defence industry is facing permanent
change and use of structural funds to assist in the management of the
transition.
Government support for large aerospace companies considering investment in
fields outside their traditional activities.
A government policy on defence diversification to study possible conversions
from defence to civil activities.
A national technological assessment to be undertaken to identify core
technologies, research and development priorities, and opportunities for
technological transfer into new product areas.
The society says that restructuring will have significant implications for
the UK's technological and manufacturing base. However, it also emphasises
that the industry does not want a return to direct government intervention
in company decision-making but a more constructive dialogue with government.
Other important warnings include the danger that reduced research and
development expenditure in the UK would result in British companies losing
their technological edge. This would weaken their position in negotiations
to form joint ventures or collaborate in international partnerships by
making them junior partners in such ventures.
The society also warns of the impact of economic recession on the corporate
acquisition process. Cash-rich companies may acquire new businesses but many
hard-pressed defence companies would find it difficult to justify a rights
issue to make a strategic purchase. It adds that if acquisitions do take
place, they risk being in countries where business activity is recovering
faster than in the UK.
The society is sending to prospective parliamentary candidates three initial
briefing papers. But it plans to maintain the pressure by producing a number
of additional papers to underline what it believes is an urgent need for
greater government support and understanding for the UK's leading
manufacturing industry.
</TEXT>
