FT  07 MAR 92 / Tory backbenchers protest government leasehold plans
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY backbenchers protested in the Commons yesterday that planned government
legislation to give all leaseholders in England and Wales the right to buy
the freehold of their property would penalise owners of houses in central
London while enabling leaseholders to 'make a killing'.
Mr William Benyon, Conservative MP for Milton Keynes, said it was a 'curious
proposal' by Conservative ministers, while Mr Steve Norris, Conservative MP
for Epping Forest, described it as 'an unConservative measure' involving the
forced sale of assets.
Mr Benyon said it would give 'an enormous immediate tax free capital gain'
to leaseholders at the expense of the current freeholder.
Questioning why residents in Eaton Square deserved so generous a 'windfall',
Mr Benyon suggested that the dissolution of the monasteries provided the
closest parallel to such an arbitrary transfer of property from one section
of the population to another.
Mr Norris, who declared his interest in Haven Services, a company which
included sheltered accommodation among its 4,000 properties, urged the
government to recognise that there were profound 'anti-libertarian' issues
at stake.
