<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 92 / Lime Street directors had Pounds 400,000 in bonuses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK, RICHARD LAPPER and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIRECTORS of Lime Street Underwriting Agencies, the Lloyd's members' agency
which went into liquidation yesterday, paid themselves Pounds 400,000 in
bonuses in June.
Heavy losses have been incurred by Names recruited to Lime Street, who were
placed in some of the syndicates with the greatest losses in recent years,
such as Gooda Walker 387, for which 1989 losses are now estimated at seven
times the assets pledged by Names - the individuals whose assets underwrite
insurance business at Lloyd's.
Meanwhile, the principal route used by MPs to make public allegations about
problems at the Lloyd's insurance market appears to have been blocked. Mr
Peter Hain, Labour MP for Neath, said he had been told by parliamentary
authorities that the Speaker would accept no further Lloyd's-related motions
in the current parliament.
Details of the Lime Street payments came at a creditors' meeting yesterday,
after a decision by the directors to put the company into creditors'
voluntary liquidation with net current liabilities of Pounds 476,000.
The bonuses were shown in unaudited accounts for the 19 months to February
1992. Bonuses in the previous three years had ranged from Pounds 20,000 to
Pounds 55,000.
After board approval last June Mr Patrick Corbett was awarded Pounds
150,000, Mr Richard Gethin-Jones and Mr Robin Kingsley Pounds 100,000 each
and Mr Robert Hallum Pounds 50,000. None was willing to say whether that
money would be returned.
Mr Ian Bond, a partner with Cork Gully and one of the liquidators, told the
meeting that Names had given notification by last Thursday of claims
totalling Pounds 21m.
Mr Robin Kingsley, founder of Lime Street and a series of associated
companies, came under repeated questioning from disgruntled Names yesterday.
They demanded to know why they were so heavily represented on loss-making
syndicates such as 387.
Mr Kingsley said he placed Names on 387 because it had performed better than
other syndicates on average in the past and gave a spread of risk across
Lloyd's. 'I am absolutely mortified by what happened. I could not be more
sorry,' he said.
Mr Hain, whose motion urging an inquiry into the Lime Street agency was
printed in Thursday's order paper, said he was seeking an interview with the
Speaker - Mr Bernard Weatherill  - to discuss the apparent blocking of
motions on Lloyd's.
The Speaker has already served warning that he would not tolerate the use of
early day motions - which enable allegations to be published under the
protection of parliamentary privilege - to mount concerted campaigns.
More than 1,500 Names facing losses of more than Pounds 150m on Feltrim
syndicates 540 and 847 in the 1989 underwriting year will not have to meet
cash calls which had been scheduled for April 30.
The syndicate's managers confirmed yesterday that the calls had been
cancelled.
Agreement is close in the long-running Outhwaite case. Eighty-one Lloyd's
agents yesterday accepted the terms of a Pounds 116m out-of-court settlement
with about 1,000 Outhwaite Names who were members of Outhwaite syndicate
317/661 in the 1982 year. The Names ratified the settlement on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
