<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 92 / 4,000 Maxwell pensions cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than 4,000 pensioners will suffer severe falls in their income from
July following the raid made on their pension fund by Mr Robert Maxwell, the
publishing tycoon who died last November, it was announced yesterday.
Pensions are likely to be cut by between a half and three-quarters.
These are the first people to be told of definite cuts in pension payments
as a result of the diversion of more than Pounds 400m of assets. Since then
30,000 current and former Maxwell employees have feared the loss of their
pensions.
The pensioners affected are members of the Maxwell Com munication Works
Pension Scheme (MWS), mostly from the printing industry. The scheme had
assets of Pounds 155m but only a small fraction of that money is left.
Mirror Group Newspapers, Mr Maxwell's British newspaper business, has been
using company funds to finance pension payments to MWS members, and will do
so until the end of June.
However, Mr Charles Wilson, editorial director of MGN, said MGN could no
longer fund the payments to non-MGN pensioners without jeopardising the
pensions of its own employees.
The news comes days before the Commons social security committee is expected
to report on the UK pension industry and Mr Maxwell. Mr Frank Field,
chairman of the committee, which is due to report on Monday, said pension
funds should be governed by company law, not trust law. He said: 'I think
voters will demand radical change.'
Kenneth Trench, of the Maxwell Pension Fund Association, said: 'What we are
calling for is a compensation scheme to be set up straight away.' He said
pensioners had been financially mugged. MGN took responsibility for the MWS
in 1989 when the pension schemes of nearly 90 Maxwell companies were
consolidated.
The MWS scheme will continue to pay reduced pensions from its remaining
assets and any assets recovered will go towards making good the shortfall in
payments.
Pension fund worries, Page 7
Concern over MGN, Page 8
